Broken Pyton

Category: Secure Coding

Objective:

Analyze a SUID C program embedding a Python interpreter, identify vulnerabilities, fix them, and retrieve the flag.

Challenge Files: /challenge/src contains program.c and supporting files.

Hints from Challenge Name:

“Broken Pyton” indicates Python is integrated incorrectly or privilege management is flawed.

Step 1: Program Overview

The program performs the following:

Argument Parsing:

Optional --no_drop flag

Optional Python code as CLI argument

Optional --help

Privilege Detection:

Retrieves real UID (RUID) and effective UID (EUID)

Prints both for debugging

Privilege Dropping (Vulnerable):

Checks if ruid != euid

Drops privileges conditionally with seteuid()

Allows bypass using --no_drop

Python Interpreter Integration:

Initializes Python (Py_Initialize)

Executes Python code if provided, else REPL

Exit:

Finalizes Python (Py_Finalize)

Returns 0

Step 2: Critical Sections of the Original Code
2.1 Argument Parsing
for (int i = 1; i < argc; i++) {
    if (strcmp(argv[i], "--no_drop") == 0) {
        no_drop = 1;
    } else if (strcmp(argv[i], "--help") == 0) {
        print_usage(argv[0]);
        return 0;
    } else {
        python_code = argv[i];
    }
}

Issues:

--no_drop allows bypass of privilege drop.

python_code can be arbitrary Python code.

Risk: Users can run Python as root.

2.2 Privilege Detection & Dropping (Vulnerable)
ruid = getuid();
euid = geteuid();

printf("Real UID: %d\n", ruid);
printf("Effective UID: %d\n", euid);

if (ruid != euid) {
    if (no_drop) {
        printf("SUID detected! --no_drop used, privileges kept.\n");
    } else {
        printf("SUID detected! Dropping privileges...\n");
        if (seteuid(ruid) == -1) {
            perror("seteuid failed");
            exit(1);
        }
        printf("Effective UID is now: %d\n", geteuid());
    }
}

Vulnerabilities:

seteuid() only drops EUID, leaving saved UID intact → reversible.

--no_drop bypass allows full root access.

Exploit Example:

import os
os.seteuid(0)  # Re-escalates to root
print(open('/flag.txt').read())
2.3 Python Execution
Py_Initialize();

if (!Py_IsInitialized()) {
    fprintf(stderr, "Failed to initialize Python interpreter\n");
    exit(1);
}

if (python_code != NULL) {
    execute_python_code(python_code);
} else {
    interactive_repl();
}

Py_Finalize();

Observation:

Python runs with current EUID.

If EUID is root due to above vulnerabilities, Python can access /flag.txt and system files.

2.4 Execute Python Function
void execute_python_code(const char *code) {
    PyObject *main_module = PyImport_AddModule("__main__");
    PyObject *main_dict = PyModule_GetDict(main_module);
    PyObject *result = PyRun_String(code, Py_single_input, main_dict, main_dict);
    if (result == NULL) PyErr_Print();
    else Py_DECREF(result);
}

Observation:

Executes any Python code in the context of the process EUID.

Combined with seteuid() vulnerability → full root shell possible.

2.5 Interactive REPL
void interactive_repl() {
    char line[1024];
    PyObject *main_module = PyImport_AddModule("__main__");
    PyObject *main_dict = PyModule_GetDict(main_module);
    
    printf(">>> ");
    while (fgets(line, sizeof(line), stdin) != NULL) {
        line[strcspn(line, "\n")] = 0;
        if (strcmp(line, "exit()") == 0 || strcmp(line, "quit()") == 0) break;
        if (strlen(line) == 0) { printf(">>> "); continue; }
        
        PyObject *result = PyRun_String(line, Py_single_input, main_dict, main_dict);
        if (result == NULL) PyErr_Print();
        else Py_DECREF(result);
        printf(">>> ");
    }
}

Observation:

Untrusted Python code can escalate privileges if EUID not dropped properly.

REPL cannot exit privilege escalation risk if SUID mishandled.

Step 3: Secure Fix
3.1 Remove --no_drop Logic
// BEFORE (vulnerable)
if (no_drop) { ... }

// AFTER (secure)
printf("SUID detected! Dropping privileges before Python execution...\n");
3.2 Use setuid() Instead of seteuid()
if (setuid(ruid) == -1) {
    perror("setuid failed");
    exit(1);
}
printf("Effective UID is now: %d\n", geteuid());

